Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient: singleton so connections are reused (avoids socket exhaustion)
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // DataService: singleton — one shared instance holds config/cache for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels: transient — each navigation gets a fresh, independent instance
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages: transient — new page instance per navigation, pairs with its ViewModel
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; avoids socket exhaustion from repeated instantiation |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Shared state (auth tokens, cache) should live once for the app's lifetime |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each page navigation needs fresh state — no stale data from a previous visit |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches ViewModel lifetime; avoids UI bugs from reused visual state |

**Key rule of thumb:** if it holds *shared app-wide state*, make it a **singleton**. If it holds *per-screen state*, make it **transient**. Avoid `AddScoped` in MAUI — there's no built-in scope-per-navigation, so it behaves like singleton and causes confusion.
